        <div id="further-information">
            <div class="furthur-information-block">
                <div class="furthur-information-block-top"></div>
                <div class="furthur-information-block-mid">
                    <div class="block">
                        <h3>Reviews by email and web</h3>
                        <h4>

Code reviews turns merge proposals into mini-mailing lists.</h4>
                        <p class="screen-holder">
                            <img src="images/hosting/2.png" alt="Reviews by email and web" width="428" height="311" />                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Launchpad emails each comment and vote to everyone taking part in the review. It also maintains public visibility, by providing a web interface to the review, thereby making it easy for new participants to join in.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="block odd">
                        <h3>Public voting</h3>
                        <h4>Public voting increases the number of people who can have their say, improving you chances of catching issues before they make it into your code-base.
                        <p class="screen-holder">
                            <img src="images/reviews/2.png" alt="Public voting" width="428" height="311" />                        </p>
                        <p>
                            When it comes to making a final decision on whether to accept someone&rsquo;s branch, you naturally give more weight to the opinions of certain people. Your project&rsquo;s community can help by voting on whether to accept or reject the proposed code. Using custom tags, each individual can even specify which aspect of the branch they&rsquo;re voting on.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="clear"></div>
                </div>
                <div class="furthur-information-block-bot"></div>
